A Basin is a Study Area composed of hydrologic elements (Subcatchments) and mainly natural hydraulic elements (Channels).
A Basin is a Study Area composed of hydrologic elements (Subcatchments) and mainly structural hydraulic elements (Pipes).
A Rainfall File is an external file storing the hyetograph(s) associated with a Storm.
A Channel Cross Section, like Pipe Shape, provides a geometric definition of a channel's cross-setcion.
A Storm is either a design storm or historical storm with a definite time period and associated rainfall hyetograph(s).
A UIC Drainage Area is the area that drains to a UIC. Generally these match surface subcatchments' drainage areas before they were reconnected to a UIC.
A Subcatchment is a surface area of drainage that drains to a node.

A Channel is a Link that always offers open channel flow. It has a trapezoidal channel shape by default but can also contain a variety of Channel Cross Sections representing varying channel geometry along the Channel's flow path.
A Tree Crown covers parts of surface subcatchments and only the parts covering impervious Rights-of-Way (streets) are considered effective in intercepting rainfall.
A Surface Subcatchment drains water from the surface that's not part of a direct subcatchment

A Direct Subcatchment is a surface area of drainage for a taxlot. Direct Subcatchments are grouped by their draining Nodes, divided between Roof and Parking, then further divided to parts that drain to Pipes, Dry Wells, Infiltration Basins, and Stormwater Planters.
A Priority List is an ordered list of a Plan's Projects that meet a Plan Objective.
A Time Frame is a physical configuration of infrastructure, generally tied to a year (2040) or abstract point in time (for example, "Existing" or "Future").
A Study Area is an area of interest to be modeled. It can include one or more distinct, unconnected Networks.
A Plan Objective is a quantitative or qualitative goal that needs to be met in order for a Plan to be successful.
A Project is a set of Alternative Packages applied to a Model to simulate changes necessary to meet a Plan's Plan Objectives.

A Plan is a set of Projects that work together to meet one or more Plan Objectives. A Plan's Projects are arranged in a Priority List since some Projects may have to be constructed before other Projects.

A CartographicProduct is a GIS product such as a workspace or map document developed for a Model or other analysis or reporting functions derived from model results. Used to check Models, report on system characteristics, modeling results, and proposed alternatives.
A Cost Estimate is a dollar cost of implementing an Alternative Package.
An Alternative Package is a set of changes to a model (Adds, Deletes, Modifications).
A Modeling Engine File is the file produced by a system to convert a Model that can be understood by a Modeling Engine.
A Roof Target is an inflow coontrol applied to a roof or building footprint.

A Simulation is the combination of products that result from a completed model run (including results, workspaces, etc.). At a minimum, a Simulation exists after a Model engine file has been generated.
A Model Result is a collection of results from an element within a simulation.
A Link Result is a Model Result for a Link (Pipe, Orifice, etc.) in a Simulation.
A CharWorkspace is a Cartographic Product for displaying basic characterization data of a study area.

A Divide is a subarea of a Taxlot that is used to redirect flow from that subarea to another location. Once a Taxlot is divided, the component areas are considered Divides and the original Taxlot is stored away for recalculation purposes. Divides must be consistent with the original Taxlot (i.e., areas must add up).
A Result Workspace is a Cartographic Product displaying the results of a Simulation.
A Modeling Engine is targeted to receive a Modeling Engine File produced when a Simulation is conceived.
A Model Scenario is a set of Models representing a common configuration (time frame, storm).
An Interface File is a binary result file from a Simulation that can be used to transfer time series data between Simulations.
A Parking Target is an Inflow Control applied to a parking lot.
A Model is a collection of objects used to analyze the hydrologic and hydraulic characteristics (existing or projected) of a sewer infrastructure.
A DSC Result is a Model Result for a DSC in a Simulation.
A Node Result is a Model Result for a Node in a Simulation.
A Street Target is an Inflow Control applied to right-of-way (ROW) area.
A DiscoVeg is an Inflow Control that shunts water from a roof to a vegetated (pervious) area. There is a chance in some circumstances where not all of the water is lost from the system.
A Taxlot is a parcel of land that is considered private property but which contributes runoff to the sewer system.
A Zoning is the legal usage of a taxlot (e.g., single family homes, commercial building, industrial warehouses, etc.). Zoning affects a Taxlot's default baseflow and future impervious growth.
A Water Billing is used to estimate the amount of sanitary sewage a Taxlot generates.

Structural: a device intended to remove or delay either flow or contaminants using either treatment, disposal, or storage. Examples include swales, on-site inflow controls, detention facilities, and UICs, Control levels expressed in terms of percent reduction, volume removed, or effluent concentration.
An Orifice is a Link that represents a sharp constriction in the flow of water in a Model.
A DryWell is an Inflow Control that shunts water from an impervious area into the ground. There is usually no chance for this water to get back into the model.

A Pump is a Link that represents a pump station between two Nodes. The upstream Node is where the pump station takes in water, and the downstream Node is where the pump station either discharges or delivers flow to a pressurized Pipe.
An Outfall is a Node that represents where water in the Model is released to a receiving water, a treatment plant, or the ground.
An Inflow Control is a device applied to a Model Element to reduce or attenuate the flow of water in a Model.
Pertains to public structures and activities intended to remove or treat stormwater. Two tiers of BMP types exist, detailed and generalized.
A Pipe Condition is a collection of attributes describing a Pipe's structural and operational characteristics.
A Pipe is a Link that represents a physical pipe (usually cylindrical, but can also be of different shapes) that provides open channel flow when not full and presurrized, closed pipe flow when full.
A UIC Well is a component of a UIC
A Green Roof is an Inflow Control that absorbs water via abstraction.
Nonstructural: any activity intended to reduce pollutants through education, waste reduction and treatment programs. Quantification of effects are usually difficult to identify.
A StorageNode is a Node that either has significantly more area per unit of depth than a normal Node or has a varying area per unit of depth.
A Link is a structural, directed connection between two Nodes.

A Node is a significant point in a model and can represent a manhole, a flow entry point, a grade break, a change in material, and other structurally significant changes in the flow of water in the physical network.
A UIC is an underground injection control (sump) that usually directs water from a subcatchment into the ground. The water is considered lost from the Model when it is run.
A Weir is a Link that blocks flow from an incoming Link up to a certain depth.
A Pipe Geometry is the geometric specification of a Pipe Shape, from the bottom to the top of the cross section.
